Potential issues: variables in C need to be declared. So variables like v1, v2, t, d, a, v, distance, i. All integers. So in C, we'll use int types. Let me outline the C code:

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int v1, v2, t, d; scanf("%d %d", &v1, &v2);
    scanf("%d %d", &t, &d);

    int a = 1;
    int v = v1;
    int distance = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < t; i++) {
        if (v - v2 > (t - i -1) * d) {
            a = -1;
            v = (t - i -1) * d + v2;
        }
        distance += v;
        v += a * d;
    }

    printf("%d\n", distance);
    return 0;
} Wait, but wait. In Python, the loop runs for t times. So for example, if t is 3, i is 0,1,2. Each iteration, the code adds v to distance. So total t times. So in C, the loop is correct as for (i=0; i < t; i++). But let's check the condition. Suppose during the loop, when i is some value, the remaining steps are (t - i -1) steps left.
